Suspected Pokot bandits on Tuesday raided Lopii, Lokori in Turkana East shot a cop, damaged police vehicles and drove away with an unknown number of livestock. Confirming the incident, Turkana East sub county police commander Edwin Ongwari said the security team who were pursuing the bandits to recover the livestock, encountered an ambush at Kachalanga village, Kakulit sub location, Kochodin ward in Lokori. The officers engaged the bandits in a fierce fire that lasted one hour injuring a police officer attached to Lokori police station who was shot on the lower left leg near the ankle. “Three land cruisers and one armoured personnel carrier were shot at and damaged,” Ongwari said. He said the security team overpowered the suspected bandits and repulsed them back towards River Kerio. In January, a senior police officer was shot and killed by suspected Pokot bandits in Kapedo area, Turkana. Three other officers were shot and wounded in the attack that occurred when the officers led a convoy of cars and responded to a distress call. The officer was a deputy head of operations at the General Service Unit in Nairobi and a superintendent of police by rank. The government imposed a 30-day curfew in parts of Baringo and Turkana in January to restore calm and order in the region. Interior Cabinet Secretary Fred Matiang’i lifted the dusk to dawn curfew in Kapedo, Turkana. The curfew that ran from 6.00 pm to 6.00 am lasted  30 days and was imposed to combat insecurity in the region. “We shall however retain the 10.00 pm-4.00 am curfew in line with the Presidential directives on the revised Covid-19 containment measures,” the Interior CS said in a statement. He said the authorities have also recovered 53 firearms in the operation, through efforts of involved security teams. Matiang’i said that peace and normalcy had resumed in the area. However, roadblocks within Kapedo shall be maintained.  Edited by Kiilu Damaris